## Page wrapper anatomy

```
udc-<id>-page (FRAME, 2800w, hug height, fill: page-subtle, radius: container-xl, clipsContent: true)
├── status-accent (RECTANGLE, 2800×8, status-tinted gradient — wrapper-level, clipped by wrapper corners)
├── content (FRAME, FILL w, hug h, autolayout V, gap: space/1000, padding: space/800)
│   ├── HEADER          (light card, taller padding)
│   ├── ANATOMY         (light card)  ← optional, omit for placeholder pages
│   ├── VARIANTS        (light card)  ← omit if no inspectable component sets
│   ├── SUB-COMPONENTS  (light card)  ← omit if no underscored components
│   ├── USAGE           (light card)
│   ├── ACCESSIBILITY   (light card)  ← optional, requires accessibility.keyboard
│   └── META            (light card, taller padding)
```

The page wrapper itself is rounded (`uds/border/radius/container-xl`,
matching the inner cards) and clips its content, so the
`status-accent` strip at the top inherits the wrapper's rounded
top-left and top-right corners. The wrapper has no stroke — the
rounded silhouette against the Figma canvas background reads as
"a single page document floating on the canvas."

The page is positioned at `(0, 0)`. Component sets are reparented INTO the appropriate cards — never duplicated, never left at top level.

## Card recipe (universal)

After the 2026-05-12 design revision, **every card on every component
page uses the same light-surface recipe.** The earlier "dark card"
treatment for HEADER and META was retired because translucent-white text
on `surface-xxbold` failed WCAG AA contrast in several theme modes (see
the accessibility note below for context).

| Property | Token / value |
|---|---|
| Fill | `uds/color/surface/surface-main` |
| Stroke | 1px `uds/color/border/border-tertiary` |
| Radius | `uds/border/radius/container-xl` (24px) |
| Effects | Dual drop shadow: `0,1,3,0 @ 4%` + `0,12,32,-4 @ 5%` |
| Inner padding (most cards) | `uds/space/800` (64px) |
| Inner padding (HEADER + META) | `uds/space/1000` (80px) — taller because they carry the bookending content |
| Inner item gap (most cards) | `uds/space/400` (32px) |
| Inner item gap (HEADER inner row) | `uds/space/600` (48px) between left column and hero preview |
| Inner item gap (META inner) | `uds/space/500` (40px) between sec-head / links-row / divider / meta-row |
| ClipsContent | true |

HEADER additionally has an 8px-tall top accent strip in
`uds/color/border/<status>` (gradient: 0.3 → 1 → 0.3 alpha) directly
above the inner row, just inside the rounded-corner clip. The 2800×8
wrapper-level `status-accent` strip at the top of `udc-<id>-page` and
the 2672×4 HEADER inner strip are both intentional — the outer strip is
the page-level status marker, the inner strip is the card-level marker.

### Why light cards everywhere

The first iteration paired `surface-xxbold` (near-black) HEADER/META
cards with `text-inverse` (near-white) text. That works in light mode
but inverts incorrectly under several theme modes (ResMan Dark,
Inhabit Light's amber surface variants) and produces text below 4.5:1
contrast against the actual rendered surface color. Settling on
`surface-main` + `text-primary` for every card moves the design within
the AA-safe surface tokens documented in
`uds-token-architecture.mdc#accessibility-contract`.

## Numbered eyebrow (every section)

Identical pattern across all 7 sections. The number is the only thing that changes (`01` HEADER, `02` ANATOMY, `03` VARIANTS, `04` SUB-COMPONENTS, `05` USAGE, `06` ACCESSIBILITY, `07` META).

```
[mono number 48-56pt]  │ 1px×32-40 vertical bar  │ KICKER (mono 11-12pt, +8% tracking)
                                                  · / section-name (mono 11pt, muted)
```

| Field | Value |
|---|---|
| Number font | Geist Mono Medium, `48px / 48` (cards) or `56px / 56` (HEADER) |
| Number color | `uds/color/text/<status>` (e.g. `text-warning` for in-progress) |
| Vertical bar | 1×32-40 rectangle, fill `uds/color/border/<status>` at 0.4-0.5 opacity |
| Kicker | Geist Mono Medium 11-12, +8% tracking, `text-<status>` |
| Sub-label | Geist Mono Regular 11, `text-secondary` (every section, since all cards are light) |

Kicker text per section:

| Section | Kicker | Sub-label |
|---|---|---|
| HEADER | `COMPONENT` | `uds-components / <UDS_VERSION>` |
| ANATOMY | `STATES & VISUAL` | `· / anatomy` |
| VARIANTS | `COMPONENT VARIANTS` | `· / variants` |
| SUB-COMPONENTS | `COMPOSITION` | `· / sub-components` |
| USAGE | `GUIDELINES` | `· / usage` |
| ACCESSIBILITY | `A11Y / WCAG` | `· / accessibility` |
| META | `RESOURCES & OWNERS` | `· / meta` |

## Section titles

Inter Bold, sits below the eyebrow. All titles bind to `text-primary`
(every card is now light).

| Section | Default title (override per JSON if richer is available) |
|---|---|
| HEADER | The component title (e.g. `Button`), 80–112px, `text-primary`, -2 to -3% tracking |
| ANATOMY | "States" or pulled from `spec.json#states[].name` summary, 32px |
| VARIANTS | "<n> variants" using the natural-language variant list (e.g. `Primary, secondary, and ghost`), 32px |
| SUB-COMPONENTS | The composition pattern in plain English (e.g. `Button groups`), 32px |
| USAGE | `When to use, when not to`, 32px |
| ACCESSIBILITY | `Keyboard & screen reader`, 32px |
| META | `Where to go from here`, 36px, `text-primary` |

## Status → token map

Per user direction "Figma is always the source of truth," status is read
from the Figma page-name stoplight prefix and treated as authoritative;
`uds-docs/uds/components/<id>/status.json` is the cross-check and gets
flagged via [`sync-figma-component-status`](../skills/sync-figma-component-status/SKILL.md)
if it disagrees. Earlier versions of this rule read status the other
way; that was inverted on 2026-05-12.

The mapping is:

| Prefix | Status (in `app.js#COMPONENT_STATUS`) | Pill label | Color tokens |
|---|---|---|---|
| 🟠 / 🟡 | `in-progress` | `IN PROGRESS` | text/border/icon/surface `-warning` |
| 🔴 | `blocked` | `BLOCKED` | `-error` |
| 🟡 (when explicitly review status) | `review` | `IN REVIEW` | `-warning` (yellow tone via mode) |
| 🟢 | `production` | `PRODUCTION READY` | `-success` |
| ⚫ / ⚫️ | `placeholder` | `NOT STARTED` | `-tertiary` (no specific status color, all neutral) |

For placeholder pages: every card stays light just like a status-colored
component page, but the eyebrow number, top accent strip, kicker, and
status pill use neutral tokens (`border-tertiary`, `text-secondary`)
instead of a status color. Don't fake an orange/green for placeholder.

## HEADER right panel ("hero preview")

A status-tinted preview frame on the right of the HEADER inner row.

| Field | Value |
|---|---|
| Width × Height | 720 × 380, FIXED both axes |
| Fill | Linear gradient — two stops, both bound to `uds/color/surface/<status>-subtle` and `uds/color/surface/<status>` (deeper) |
| Radius | `uds/border/radius/container-lg` (16px) |
| Children (top to bottom, centered) | 4×16 dot pattern (5px ellipses, fill `border-<status>`, opacity 0.55, gap 28×28); ONE instance of the default variant of the primary/main component set; Geist Mono caption (e.g. `DEFAULT · PRIMARY · MEDIUM`) in `text-<status>` |

For placeholder pages with no inspectable component, the hero shows a "no component yet" treatment: skip the dot pattern and instance, fill the panel with `surface-subtle`, place a single mono label `PLACEHOLDER · COMPONENT NOT YET BUILT` centered.

## Pill row (HEADER, just under description)

Horizontal auto-layout, items in this exact order:

1. **Status pill** — `surface-<status>` at 0.18 opacity bg, 1px `border-<status>` stroke, full-radius. Contents: 8px ellipse `icon-<status>`, Geist Mono Medium 12 label (uppercase, +8% tracking, `text-<status>`).
2. **CSS chip** — `surface-subtle` bg, 1px `border-tertiary` stroke, full-radius. Contents: Geist Mono Regular 12 `text-secondary`, value `uds/components/<id>/<id>.css` (the on-disk path).
3. **Spacer** (auto-fill, takes remaining space).

Earlier versions of this rule defined two trailing items — a "View docs"
button and a "Storybook" button — in this row. Both were removed on
2026-05-12 because the links didn't work and there was already a richer
treatment for the same destinations in the META section's link cards.
Don't add new trailing items here without a design conversation.

## META link cards

Two prominent cards in a HORIZONTAL auto-layout, item gap `space/300` (24px). Both FILL width.

| Card | Style | Kicker | Title (Inter Bold 28, -1%) | URL (Geist Mono Regular 12) |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Primary (UDS Docs) | `surface-subtle` fill, 1px `border-tertiary` stroke, `radius/container-lg` | `SPEC` | `UDS Docs page` | `https://udsdocs.com/?#<id>` |
| Secondary (Storybook) | `surface-subtle` fill, 1px `border-tertiary` stroke, `radius/container-lg` | `CODE` | `Open in Storybook` | `https://storybook/?path=/story/<id> (placeholder)` |

Both cards have a top row with kicker on the left and a Geist Mono Bold
22 `↗` on the right. Title text binds to `text-primary`; URL text binds
to `text-secondary`. The 2026-05-12 design revision unified both cards
to the same subtle treatment because the previous "solid white vs
translucent white on dark surface" pairing relied on the (now retired)
dark META card.

**Docs hostname:** `udsdocs.com` (the live UDS doc site). Earlier rules
referenced `uds-docs/` as a placeholder hostname; replace with
`udsdocs.com` wherever it appears.

Below the link cards: a 1px divider (`border-tertiary`) full-width, then the META meta-row with these fields (in this order, gap `space/600`):

| Label | Value | Font |
|---|---|---|
| `DESIGNER` | `<owner.designer>` from `spec.json` | Inter Semi Bold 16, `text-primary` |
| `DEVELOPER` | `<owner.developer>` from `spec.json` | Inter Semi Bold 16, `text-primary` |
| `CSS` | `uds/components/<id>/<id>.css` (on-disk path) | Geist Mono Regular 13, `text-primary` |
| `SPEC JSON` | `uds/components/<id>/spec.json` | Geist Mono Regular 13, `text-primary` |
| `GENERATED` | ISO timestamp the agent stamped when this card was last rebuilt, e.g. `2026-05-12 15:43 UTC` | Geist Mono Regular 13, `text-secondary` |
| (spacer fill) |  |  |
| Status pill | Same recipe as HEADER's status pill | Geist Mono Medium 12 |

Every meta-row label uses Geist Mono Medium 11 uppercase, +8% tracking,
`text-secondary`. The `GENERATED` field was added on 2026-05-12 — it's a
provenance marker, NOT a content field from `spec.json`. The card
builder MUST stamp it from the system clock at build time (UTC). Do not
hand-edit; rebuild the card to refresh.

## Section content rules

Driven by `uds-docs/uds/components/<id>/spec.json` (conforms to `uds-docs/uds/schemas/spec.schema.json`). Match the existing "empty fields are hidden" rule from [`uds-content-schema.mdc`](./uds-content-schema.mdc).

The skill READS spec.json, never writes it. Same for `status.json`, `changelog.json`, `impl.json`, and `examples/*.html` — see [`uds-source-of-truth.mdc`](./uds-source-of-truth.mdc).

All JSON fields below refer to keys in `uds-docs/uds/components/<id>/spec.json` unless otherwise noted.

| Section | Required JSON fields | Behavior when empty |
|---|---|---|
| HEADER | `title`, `description`, `dependencies.css`, `owner` | If `description` empty, omit the description text but keep the rest |
| ANATOMY | An inspectable component set with named state variants (`State=Default/Hover/Active/Disabled` minimum) | If no states inspectable, OMIT the entire ANATOMY card. Don't fake states. |
| VARIANTS | At least one `COMPONENT_SET` at the page top level | If none, OMIT the VARIANTS card |
| SUB-COMPONENTS | Component sets named with leading underscore (e.g. `_udc-dialog_header`) OR explicit sub-set component sets like `udc-button-group-*` | If none, OMIT the SUB-COMPONENTS card |
| USAGE | `whenToUse` AND/OR `whenNotToUse` | If both empty, OMIT |
| ACCESSIBILITY | `accessibility.keyboard` non-empty | If empty, OMIT (no point showing an empty table) |
| META | Always shown — owners and links are universal |

When a section is omitted, the eyebrow numbers stay in **rendering order**. So a page with no SUB-COMPONENTS goes `01 → 02 → 03 → 05 → 06 → 07` (skipping 04). DON'T renumber. Maintains stable mental model across components.

## What NOT to do

- **No raw hex anywhere.** Every `fills`, `strokes`, paint, and (where applicable) padding/gap/radius MUST be bound to a `uds/*` library variable. The literal `color` value in a paint object is fine and required (it sets the design-time appearance), but the binding is what survives mode changes.
- **Don't introduce new top-level nodes on the page.** Reparent existing component sets into the cards; never duplicate them, never leave them at page level.
- **Don't fake content.** Empty JSON fields → omitted card. Don't paste placeholder lorem ipsum just to fill a card.
- **Don't hardcode component IDs in the rule or skill.** The skill must discover state variant ids by parsing the component-set children's `name` field for `State=...` patterns. The same logic must work across every component without code changes.
- **Don't change the card order.** It's `HEADER → ANATOMY → VARIANTS → SUB-COMPONENTS → USAGE → ACCESSIBILITY → META`. Always.
- **Don't put the new card layout into the mainline `UDS Components` Figma file** without the user explicitly saying "mainline".
- **Don't bump the SITE version for changes confined to `.cursor/`.** This rule lives outside `uds-docs/`, so it does NOT trigger [`uds-master-preflight.mdc`](./uds-master-preflight.mdc) / [`uds-site-changelog.mdc`](./uds-site-changelog.mdc). The Figma builder script (if added under `.cursor/skills/figma-component-card/references/`) is also outside `uds-docs/`.

## Order of operations (every agent run)

1. **Pre-flight per [`uds-figma-preflight.mdc`](./uds-figma-preflight.mdc).** Read-only inspection first.
2. **Discover.** Read the matching `_TEMPLATE` page in the Figma file FIRST (page name starts with `📐 _TEMPLATE`). If the template differs from this rule, the template wins — designers can override here without touching code.
3. **Confirm tokens are subscribed.** `get_libraries` should show `UDS Tokens` in `libraries_added_to_file`. If not, ask the user to subscribe — don't auto-subscribe.
4. **Read the JSON spec.** `uds-docs/uds/components/<id>/spec.json` and `status.json`. If `spec.json` doesn't exist, the page is a placeholder.
5. **Inspect the page's existing nodes.** Find component sets, sub-components, the page-name prefix. Cross-check status with `status.json#current`.
6. **Confirm the user-authorized write scope.** Per [`uds-figma-write-safety.mdc`](./uds-figma-write-safety.mdc), this skill only runs when the user has named the target (single component, batch, or library-wide). Do not invoke as a side effect of another task.
7. **Run the builder.** Single `use_figma` call per component (per the skill).
8. **Emit the Figma write summary.** Per [`uds-figma-write-safety.mdc`](./uds-figma-write-safety.mdc), every write produces a structured before/after report.
9. **Audit.** The `figma-component-card-audit` subagent verifies the result.

## Required Figma write summary

After every component card build (per [`uds-figma-write-safety.mdc`](./uds-figma-write-safety.mdc)), the agent MUST return:

```markdown
## Figma write summary

- File: UDS Components | UDS Components Testbed
- File key: ...
- Page: <emoji + component-id>
- Node/frame: udc-<id>-page (root frame), plus content + 7 section cards
- Operation: create | rebuild | update
- Old value: <if rebuilding: prior wrapper structure brief>
- New value: <new wrapper dimensions and section list>
- Component sets reparented: <list of IDs and their new parent cards>
- Component sets duplicated/deleted: <should be empty — flag if not>
- Rollback note: existing component sets are reparented in place; revert by re-parenting back to page level and deleting the udc-<id>-page wrapper
```

For batch runs, return one summary block per component, plus a top-level batch summary with counts.

## Mainline rollout protocol

Once a component card is approved on the testbed and the audit passes:

1. Get user approval to push to mainline (`UDS Components`, file key `1XJoUJgtNpw4R0IIT3VjoK`)
2. Re-run the builder targeting the mainline file key
3. Re-run the audit on the mainline page
4. Per [`uds-release-workflow.mdc`](./uds-release-workflow.mdc), if this changes how the spec is published, also update the version cover in the mainline file

